iblings, than if had he molested him. Everyone is entitled to express their religious beliefs in the way most appropriate to them- no argument there- but that does not include having 11 children and raising them in a state of gross ignorance, unable to cope with the outside world. There has to be some way to prevent the unrepentant Quiver crazed adults from destroying these innocent lives. If the only way one can assure that one's children are godly and appreciate one's faith is to keep them in everlasting ignorance, that is no faith at all- it is a cult. All the great spiritual leaders and founders of faith communities have walked among the people, not hidden is covens as the Powells appear to do. Farris' desire to make the parent's decisions absolute fails to take into consideration what others do in the name of their perceived God which can lead to injury and death, vis: a recent case where the parents prayed over their child rather than take it to the doctor which would have saved the child's life. . As a devout practicer of my faith, I am disgusted and outraged by this story and admire Joshua's courage in light of this malignant parental idiocy. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1476" language="en" documentId="22" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="slmdarien" date="7/30/2013 8:00 PM GMT+0200" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://www.washingtonpost.com/local/students-home-schooling-highlights-debate-over-va-religious-exemption-law/2013/07/28/ee2dbb1a-efbc-11e2-bed3-b9b6fe264871_comment.html?commentID=washingtonpost.com/ECHO/item/1375207258-486-98" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="22" notes="" title="Student’s home-schooling highlights debate over Va. religious exemption law"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1476"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39"/></xmi:XMI>